where
* formula_270, formula_271 is equal to 1, 2 or 3 for formula_72, formula_73, and formula_71, respectively,
* formula_275 is the vector to the point mass formula_276 from the point about which the tensor is calculated and
* formula_277 is the Kronecker delta.

Note that, by the definition, formula_278 is a symmetric tensor.

The diagonal elements are more succinctly written as
formula_279

while the off-diagonal elements, also called the , are
formula_280

Here formula_46 denotes the moment of inertia around the formula_72-axis when the objects are rotated around the x-axis, formula_283 denotes the moment of inertia around the formula_73-axis when the objects are rotated around the formula_72-axis, and so on.

These quantities can be generalized to an object with distributed mass, described by a mass density function, in a similar fashion to the scalar moment of inertia. One then has
formula_286

where formula_287 is their outer product, E3 is the 3×3 identity matrix, and &quot;V&quot; is a region of space completely containing the object.

Alternatively it can also be written in terms of the angular momentum operator formula_288:
formula_289

